04133nam a22005895i 9780822380894DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223808947 a10.1515/97808223808942doi  a(DE-B1597)553939  a(OCoLC)1226678421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR2880 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.3/31 aTatlow, Antony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShakespeare, Brecht, and the Intercultural Sign /cAntony Tatlow; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (308 p.) :b9 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tPrologue -- t1 Reading the Intercultural: Cultures of Reading -- t2 Intercultural Signs: Textual Anthropology -- t3 Desire, Laughter, and the Social Unconscious -- t4 Historicizing the Unconscious in Plautine and Shakespearean Farce -- t5 Coriolanus and the Historical Text -- t6 Macbeth in Kunju Opera -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Shakespeare, Brecht, and the Intercultural Sign renowned Brecht scholar Antony Tatlow uses drama to investigate cultural crossings and to show how intercultural readings or performances question the settled assumptions we bring to interpretations of familiar texts. Through a "textual anthropology" Tatlow examines the interplay between interpretations of Shakespeare and readings of Brecht, whose work he rereads in the light of theories of the social subject from Nietzsche to Derrida and in relation to East Asian culture, as well as practices within Chinese and Japanese theater that shape their versions of Shakespearean drama.Reflecting on how, why, and to what effect knowledges and styles of performance pollinate across cultures, Tatlow demonstrates that the employment of one culture's material in the context of another defamiliarizes the conventions of representation in an act that facilitates access to what previously had been culturally repressed. By reading the intercultural, Tatlow shows, we are able not only to historicize the effects of those repressions that create a social unconscious but also gain access to what might otherwise have remained invisible.This remarkable study will interest students of cultural interaction and aesthetics, as well as readers interested in theater, Shakespeare, Brecht, China, and Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIntercultural communication in literaturexHistory. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aTheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380894zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822380894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822380894.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles